PART 5 - HOW TO WRITE EACH FIELD
================================

ROWS
====

1. Normal row fields
--------------------
Use comma-separated source columns.

Example:
Agent,Campaign Name


2. Custom row rules
-------------------
Format:
Label: Field=Value & Field2=Value2

Example:
Morning: Time Band=Morning & Team=Call

Meaning:
- create a row label named Morning
- include only source rows matching all parts

Supported here:
- & means AND

Important:
Custom row rules must match at least one source row.


ROW NAMES
=========

Optional.
Use this only if you want to rename rows for display.

Keep the same order as Rows.


VALUES TO COUNT/SUM
===================

Put the source fields you want summarized.

Examples:
Policy No.
Premium
Premium,Policy No.

Tips:
- use number fields if you want Sum
- use text fields if you want Count


FILTERS
=======

Supported forms:

1. Just show a filter field
---------------------------
Campaign Name


2. Preselect values
-------------------
Status=Open,Closed


3. Multiple filter fields
-------------------------
Status=Open,Closed; Region=East


Rules:
- use ; to separate different filter fields
- use , to separate multiple selected values in the same field
- line breaks are normalized by the script


CONDITIONS
==========

Conditions create condition-based pivot columns/categories.

1. Simple condition
-------------------
Status=Open


2. Multiple condition items
---------------------------
Status=Open; Region=East


3. Condition with label
-----------------------
Open Case: Status=Open


4. Compare to another source column
-----------------------------------
Paid Date=[Answer Date]

or

Paid Date=@Answer Date


5. Condition with measure field
-------------------------------
Open Case: Status=Open => Policy No.


6. AND / OR
-----------
Status=Open AND Region=East

Status=Open OR Status=Pending


Best practice:
- use one condition item per ;
- keep each item simple if possible


PART 6 - CALCULATED COLUMNS
===========================

This is the most powerful part.

Basic format:
Name: Formula

Multiple calculated columns:
USD: Premium*{THB to USD}; Reach: Contactable+Uncontactable


MATH
====

Supported operators:
- +
- -
- *
- /

Examples:
USD: Premium*{THB to USD}
Gap: Target-Actual
Rate: Paid/Total


IF
==

Supported:
IF(condition, true_value)
IF(condition, true_value, false_value)

If only 2 parts are given, false becomes blank automatically.

Examples:
Flag: IF(Premium>0,"Yes","No")
PaidFlag: IF(Paid Date!="","Paid")


NESTED IF
=========

Supported.

Example:
Band: IF(Score>=80,"High",IF(Score>=50,"Medium","Low"))


COMPARISON OPERATORS
====================

Supported:
>
<
=
!=
>=
<=

Use:
- = not ==
- != not <>

Examples:
Amount>10
Status="Open"
Region!="East"


TEXT VALUES
===========

Put text in quotes.

Examples:
"Yes"
"10 or more"
"Morning"


BLANK CHECK
===========

Examples:
Paid Date=""
Paid Date!=""


MONTHLY INPUTS
==============

You can use monthly input values in formulas.

Examples:
{Month}
{THB to USD}

Example formula:
USD: Amount*{THB to USD}


PIVOT LOOKUPS
=============

You can pull values from another built pivot.

Format:
PivotName[row=Row Label, column=Column Label]

Examples:
Pivot_1[row=*, column=Contactable]
KPI!Pivot_1[row=Agent A, column=Grand Total]

Meaning of row=* :
use the current row label


IMPORTANT LIMITS FOR CALCULATED COLUMNS
=======================================

1. Must be:
   Name: Formula

2. Do not use cell addresses like:
   E4

3. Use pivot lookup format instead of cell address if referencing pivots.

4. Use:
   = not ==

5. Use:
   != not <>


PART 7 - RAW COLUMN MODE
========================

If:
Input Sheet = Output Sheet

then that setup row does NOT build a pivot.

Instead it:
- appends raw columns
- updates raw columns
- uses Calculated Columns on that same sheet

This is useful for helper columns before building pivots.

Examples:
MonthName: {Month}
USD: Premium*{THB to USD}
Time Band: IF(Hour<12,"Morning","Noon")


